abstract: Google’s offer to build a high-speed broadband network in cities has brought out a competitive spirit nationwide.

lead_paragraph: The mayor of Duluth, Minn., threw himself into the ice-ringed waters of Lake Superior. The mayor of Sarasota, Fla., immersed himself in a tank filled with bonnethead sharks, simply to one-up him. The mayor of Wilmington, N.C., said that he would even jump out of an airplane — with a parachute, of course.

headline.main: Hoping for Gift From Google? Go Jump in the Lake

abstract: The founders of Skype will launch a second venture capital fund under their Atomico Ventures which will invest in “disruptive” early-stage technology. They have raised $165 million for the new fund, The Financial Times reported.
snippet: The founders of Skype will launch a second venture capital fund under their Atomico Ventures which will invest in “disruptive” early-stage technology. They have raised $165 million for the new fund, The Financial Times reported.
lead_paragraph: The founders of Skype will launch a second venture capital fund under their Atomico Ventures which will invest in so-called “disruptive” early-stage European technology. Niklas Zennström and Janus Friis, the founders of the company, have raised $165 million for the new fund, The Financial Times reported.

headline.main: Skype Founders Raise $165 Million for New Fund

abstract: Google said it would direct users to an uncensored version based in Hong Kong. China on Tuesday said the case would not affect ties with the U.S. “unless politicized” by others.
snippet: Google said it would direct users to an uncensored version based in Hong Kong. China on Tuesday said the case would not affect ties with the U.S. “unless politicized” by others.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Just over two months after threatening to leave China because of censorship and intrusions from hackers, Google on Monday closed its Internet search service there and began directing users in that country to its uncensored search engine in Hong Kong.

headline.main: Google Shuts China Site in Dispute Over Censorship
headline.print_headline: Google Closes Search Service Based In China

byline.original: By Miguel Helft and David Barboza

abstract: A Google founder said the shift of its Chinese service to Hong Kong was not given a clear-cut stamp of approval by Beijing.
